1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:05,120
For centuries, Italy was a kind of intellectual beacon for the entire world,

2
00:00:05,120 --> 00:00:08,000
then almost suddenly everything went dark.

3
00:00:08,000 --> 00:00:12,560
Today we try to understand why, by investigating a key moment in our history

4
00:00:12,560 --> 00:00:17,120
to discover why the cradle of the Renaissance at a certain point ground to a halt.

5
00:00:17,120 --> 00:00:19,760
And this is the central question.

6
00:00:19,760 --> 00:00:23,199
As simple as it is, well, staggering.

7
00:00:23,199 --> 00:00:28,560
How is it possible that the very nation that gave the world Leonardo, Michelangelo,

8
00:00:28,600 --> 00:00:34,080
the scientific Renaissance, suddenly lost its intellectual leadership?

9
00:00:34,080 --> 00:00:35,600
It is a true mystery.

10
00:00:35,600 --> 00:00:39,600
So let's dive into the heart of the mystery of the Italian decline,

11
00:00:39,600 --> 00:00:44,560
and it's not just a simple academic question, it's a real historical enigma

12
00:00:44,560 --> 00:00:48,240
that has left scholars perplexed for generations.

13
00:00:48,240 --> 00:00:51,520
The contrast is crazy to think about.

14
00:00:51,520 --> 00:00:56,320
On one hand, we have Renaissance Italy, an engine of knowledge and innovation.

15
00:00:56,399 --> 00:01:01,039
On the other, Italy in the following centuries, being overtaken by new intellectual

16
00:01:01,039 --> 00:01:03,840
powers like Great Britain and Germany.

17
00:01:03,840 --> 00:01:06,159
A true overtaking.

18
00:01:06,159 --> 00:01:09,680
And here, well, here the numbers speak for themselves.

19
00:01:09,680 --> 00:01:11,040
Let's look at Italy.

20
00:01:11,040 --> 00:01:14,719
The average output of publications for each scholar collapses,

21
00:01:14,719 --> 00:01:17,960
literally, from 93 to 27.

22
00:01:17,960 --> 00:01:23,319
In the exact same period, Great Britain shoots up from 77 to 137,

23
00:01:23,320 --> 00:01:26,360
Germany from 47 to 97.

24
00:01:26,360 --> 00:01:29,000
So we're not talking about a slowdown.

25
00:01:29,000 --> 00:01:33,720
It's a vertical collapse, right as the rest of Europe was hitting the turbo.

26
00:01:33,720 --> 00:01:37,080
So, where do we start to solve this thriller?

27
00:01:37,080 --> 00:01:40,360
The answer, according to some very interesting research,

28
00:01:40,360 --> 00:01:43,000
is hidden right between the pages of books,

29
00:01:43,000 --> 00:01:48,120
or perhaps it would be better to say between the pages of books that could no longer be read.

30
00:01:48,120 --> 00:01:53,200
The main tool of this control was it, the Index of Prohibited Books.

31
00:01:53,240 --> 00:01:56,159
And it wasn't just a simple reading recommendation, mind you.

32
00:01:56,159 --> 00:01:59,120
It was a real official blacklist.

33
00:01:59,120 --> 00:02:01,920
If you were caught possessing or reading one of these books,

34
00:02:01,920 --> 00:02:04,480
the consequences could be very heavy,

35
00:02:04,480 --> 00:02:07,120
from excommunication to the confiscation of all property.

36
00:02:07,120 --> 00:02:10,319
And here we find our first clue.

37
00:02:10,319 --> 00:02:12,599
The red areas on this graph

38
00:02:12,599 --> 00:02:18,599
represent the authors censored between 1540 and 1609.

39
00:02:18,599 --> 00:02:19,960
Notice one thing.

40
00:02:20,000 --> 00:02:22,000
The Index didn't hit at random.

41
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:25,360
It aimed high, specifically targeting the top tier,

42
00:02:25,360 --> 00:02:28,040
meaning the most brilliant and prolific authors,

43
00:02:28,040 --> 00:02:30,560
those you see on the right side of the graph.

44
00:02:30,560 --> 00:02:35,240
Names like Galileo Galilei, Giordano Bruno, Nicolaus Copernicus,

45
00:02:35,240 --> 00:02:37,879
so we're not talking about marginal figures.

46
00:02:37,879 --> 00:02:41,200
These were the intellectual giants of their time,

47
00:02:41,200 --> 00:02:46,040
people who were literally rewriting our understanding of the universe.

48
00:02:46,040 --> 00:02:49,200
And their works, their most revolutionary ideas,

49
00:02:49,200 --> 00:02:51,800
were simply silenced.

50
00:02:51,800 --> 00:02:55,960
Okay, let's jump forward about 150 years.

51
00:02:55,960 --> 00:02:59,000
The situation has changed, censorship is still there,

52
00:02:59,000 --> 00:03:01,360
here it is, but look at the graph.

53
00:03:01,360 --> 00:03:03,360
The red area has shifted.

54
00:03:03,360 --> 00:03:07,480
Now it targets less prolific, less dangerous authors.

55
00:03:07,480 --> 00:03:08,960
What happened?

56
00:03:08,960 --> 00:03:10,840
It seems that the most brilliant minds

57
00:03:10,840 --> 00:03:13,840
stopped writing controversial works.

58
00:03:13,840 --> 00:03:17,600
This is what scholars call the chilling effect.

59
00:03:17,599 --> 00:03:19,919
[No change needed for English]

60
00:03:19,919 --> 00:03:24,199
The point is that there was no longer even a need to censor great thinkers.

61
00:03:24,199 --> 00:03:28,400
Because great thinkers, partly out of fear, partly out of pure pragmatism,

62
00:03:28,400 --> 00:03:30,959
had begun to censor themselves,

63
00:03:30,959 --> 00:03:35,439
carefully avoiding any topic that could get them into trouble.

64
00:03:35,439 --> 00:03:40,159
And this leads us straight to the heart of the theory explaining the Italian decline,

65
00:03:40,159 --> 00:03:43,120
a theory that's not just about banned books,

66
00:03:43,120 --> 00:03:47,439
but about the life choices and careers of the smartest people in the country.

67
00:03:47,599 --> 00:03:49,719
The key concept is this:

68
00:03:49,719 --> 00:03:51,800
Talent Misallocation.

69
00:03:51,800 --> 00:03:54,960
Simply put, if following revolutionary ideas

70
00:03:54,960 --> 00:03:57,319
can lead you to the stake or to prison,

71
00:03:57,319 --> 00:04:02,159
while a quiet career in canon law guarantees you security and prestige,

72
00:04:02,159 --> 00:04:05,400
well, for many, the choice becomes almost mandatory.

73
00:04:05,400 --> 00:04:10,240
On one side was the non-compliant path, risky, full of dangers,

74
00:04:10,240 --> 00:04:12,840
but with the potential to change the world.

75
00:04:12,879 --> 00:04:17,639
On the other, the compliant path, safe, approved by the establishment,

76
00:04:17,639 --> 00:04:20,519
but intellectually much less bold.

77
00:04:20,519 --> 00:04:23,959
Censorship made the first option so dangerous

78
00:04:23,959 --> 00:04:26,840
as to push the best talents toward the second.

79
00:04:26,840 --> 00:04:29,600
Let's look at the chain of events, the domino effect.

80
00:04:29,600 --> 00:04:32,840
First, the Church censors the most innovative ideas.

81
00:04:32,840 --> 00:04:36,519
Second, the risk of dealing with those ideas increases out of proportion.

82
00:04:36,519 --> 00:04:41,280
Third, the best scholars shift toward safer and less controversial fields.

83
00:04:41,320 --> 00:04:44,960
Final result: overall innovation in Italy collapses.

84
00:04:44,960 --> 00:04:48,320
A systematic and incredibly effective mechanism.

85
00:04:48,320 --> 00:04:51,200
But is it possible to put a number on this impact?

86
00:04:51,200 --> 00:04:55,240
Can the real cost of this intellectual silence be quantified?

87
00:04:55,240 --> 00:04:59,480
Well, the research we're examining tried to do exactly that.

88
00:04:59,480 --> 00:05:04,640
It created a model to estimate how much knowledge, how many ideas Italy lost,

89
00:05:04,640 --> 00:05:07,040
precisely because of this mechanism.

90
00:05:07,160 --> 00:05:09,200
And here it is, the number.

91
00:05:09,200 --> 00:05:13,520
And it's a number that is truly impressive: 43%.

92
00:05:13,520 --> 00:05:16,360
According to estimates, without the Church's censorship,

93
00:05:16,360 --> 00:05:20,840
knowledge production in Italy would have been 43% higher.

94
00:05:20,840 --> 00:05:22,160
Let's think about it for a moment.

95
00:05:22,160 --> 00:05:27,600
Almost half of the potential scientific and cultural output simply vanished.

96
00:05:27,600 --> 00:05:30,520
And this slide shows us a fundamental point.

97
00:05:30,520 --> 00:05:35,400
The loss isn't just due to the books that were actually blacklisted.

98
00:05:35,440 --> 00:05:37,320
That's only half the damage.

99
00:05:37,320 --> 00:05:41,320
The other half, equally devastating, is the indirect effect.

100
00:05:41,320 --> 00:05:46,360
Diverted talents, changed careers, ideas that were never even born.

101
00:05:46,360 --> 00:05:50,880
And if anyone thinks the decline was caused only by economic factors,

102
00:05:50,880 --> 00:05:53,040
like the crisis of trade routes,

103
00:05:53,040 --> 00:05:55,880
well, the data suggests another story.

104
00:05:55,880 --> 00:05:59,080
The negative impact of censorship, according to this study,

105
00:05:59,080 --> 00:06:03,080
was almost four times heavier than that of the economic crisis.

106
00:06:03,080 --> 00:06:05,080
The cultural factor, in this case,

107
00:06:05,079 --> 00:06:07,479
far outperformed the economic one.

108
00:06:07,479 --> 00:06:11,639
And thus we come to the central point: the cost of silence.

109
00:06:11,639 --> 00:06:15,759
Not only that imposed from above, but also and, perhaps, above all,

110
00:06:15,759 --> 00:06:18,319
that which people imposed on themselves.

111
00:06:18,319 --> 00:06:21,759
A cost that Italy has carried for centuries.

112
00:06:21,759 --> 00:06:25,039
This sentence summarizes the tragedy perfectly.

113
00:06:25,039 --> 00:06:28,759
We will never know who the new Galileos could have been.

114
00:06:28,759 --> 00:06:33,639
Maybe they became ecclesiastical lawyers or perhaps court poets.

115
00:06:33,639 --> 00:06:39,479
Their unique and powerful talents were reassigned to safe tasks,

116
00:06:39,479 --> 00:06:42,719
but far from the frontier of knowledge.

117
00:06:42,719 --> 00:06:47,519
And this leaves us with a question that's impossible to answer,

118
00:06:47,519 --> 00:06:49,719
but fundamental to ask.

119
00:06:49,719 --> 00:06:52,279
It's not just about what we lost,

120
00:06:52,279 --> 00:06:55,279
but about what was never even created.

121
00:06:55,279 --> 00:06:58,000
How many discoveries, how many works of art,

122
00:06:58,000 --> 00:07:01,480
how many revolutions of thought were stifled

123
00:07:01,480 --> 00:07:03,879
before they could even see the light?

124
00:07:03,879 --> 00:07:08,480
This, in the end, is the true, incalculable cost of silence.

